{
title: "3.0: Interfaces",
query: "PREFIX inst: <http://example.org/botTest#> PREFIX bot: <https://w3id.org/bot#> CONSTRUCT WHERE { ?space a bot:Space ; bot:adjacentElement ?element . ?element a bot:Element . ?interface a bot:Interface ; bot:interfaceOf ?x . }",
triples: "@prefix bot: <https://w3id.org/bot#> . @prefix rdf: <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#> . @prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> . @prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> . @prefix inst: <http://example.org/botTest#> . ############## # ABOX ############## inst:SpaceA12 a bot:Space ; bot:adjacentElement inst:Wall22 . inst:ZoneB a bot:Space ; bot:adjacentElement inst:Wall22 . inst:Wall22 a bot:Element . inst:InterfaceA a bot:Interface ; bot:interfaceOf inst:SpaceA12 , inst:Wall . inst:InterfaceB a bot:Interface ; bot:interfaceOf inst:ZoneB , inst:Wall .",
description: "Interfaces between two zones, an element and a zone or two elements can be quantified using the `bot:Interface` class. In this example, interfaces are used to define heat transmission areas as an interface between a zone and it's adjacent building element. ![alt text](./assets/interfaces.png "Zones can be contained in other zones transitively")"
},
{
title: "3.1: Interfaces",
query: "PREFIX inst: <http://example.org/botTest#> PREFIX bot: <https://w3id.org/bot#> CONSTRUCT WHERE { ?space bot:adjacentElement ?el . ?interface bot:interfaceOf ?x . ?space ?sProp ?sVal . ?el ?eProp ?eVal . ?interface ?iProp ?iVal . }",
triples: "@prefix bot: <https://w3id.org/bot#> . @prefix rdf: <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#> . @prefix cdt: <http://w3id.org/lindt/custom_datatypes#> . @prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> . @prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> . @prefix inst: <http://example.org/botTest#> . @prefix props: <https://w3id.org/product/props/> . ############## # ABOX ############## inst:SpaceA12 a bot:Space ; bot:adjacentElement inst:Wall22 ; props:ambientDesignDryBulbTemperature "20 Cel"^^cdt:temperature . inst:ZoneB a bot:Space ; bot:adjacentElement inst:Wall22 ; props:ambientDesignDryBulbTemperature "20 Cel"^^cdt:temperature . inst:Wall22 a bot:Element ; props:nominalHeatTransferCoefficient "0.21 W/(m2.K)"^^cdt:ucum . inst:InterfaceA a bot:Interface ; bot:interfaceOf inst:SpaceA12 , inst:Wall ; props:heatExchangeSurfaceArea "5.3 m2"^^cdt:area . inst:InterfaceB a bot:Interface ; bot:interfaceOf inst:ZoneB , inst:Wall ; props:heatExchangeSurfaceArea "12.1 m2"^^cdt:area .",
description: "This is a further development of the dataset from the previous tab where we used interfaces to quantify heat transmission areas. We further add properties to the zones, elements and interfaces using properties from the preliminary [props](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/w3c-lbd-cg/props/master/IFC4-output.ttl) parsed from IFC4 by Maxime Lefran√ßois. Units are specified using custom datatypes for the [Unified Code of Units of Measures](http://unitsofmeasure.org/trac). Please see the [specification](https://ci.mines-stetienne.fr/lindt/v2/custom_datatypes.html#) and test its capabilities using this [playground](https://ci.mines-stetienne.fr/lindt/playground.html). CDT allows the user to query for a property in the desired unit. The following query would, for instance, return the heat transfer coefficient of all building elements in BTU/(h.ft2.K) if the SPARQL engine supported this functionality. ``` SELECT * WHERE { # get heat transfer coefficient in whatever unit given as an ucum custom datatype ?el props:nominalHeatTransferCoefficient ?value . # Convert to BTU/(h.ft2.K) by adding "0 [Btu]/(h.[ft_i]2.K)" to the initial value BIND("0 [Btu]/(h.[ft_i]2.K)"^^cdt:ucum + ?value AS ?normalized ) } ``` For UCUM codes, please see [The Unified Code for Units of Measure code system](http://unitsofmeasure.org/ucum.html). Try the following query with the [playground tool ](https://ci.mines-stetienne.fr/lindt/playground.html) to get an idea of its capabilities when working with units: ``` SELECT ?u ?a ?dt ?heatLoss WHERE{ BIND("0.21 W/(m2.K)"^^cdt:ucum as ?u) BIND("5.3 m2"^^cdt:ucum as ?a) BIND("32 K"^^cdt:ucum as ?dt) # normalize BIND(?u * ?a * ?dt AS ?heatLoss ) } ```"
}
